AUDIO: 'This is a new AI relighting&nbsp; technique almost no one’s heard of,&nbsp;&nbsp; and it’s a bit like recreating the&nbsp; Mona Lisa in a laser-lit club night. So, we talk about 3D modeling programs like&nbsp; Blender here, where you can create a 3D scene,&nbsp;&nbsp; and change the lighting with just one click. But&nbsp; that is not the case for real 2D photographs. For&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these, we load up Photoshop and even today, in the&nbsp; age of AI, we can’t easily move a light source,&nbsp;&nbsp; we can only do these pitiful edits to it,&nbsp; like changing the contrast. By the way,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this not me, I can only wish I could&nbsp; rock a fabulous mustache like that.&nbsp; So, the old rule still stands:&nbsp; the light is permanent. Until now. This amazing new paper promises a new&nbsp; way to relight a 2D photograph. Let’s see…let’s&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'take this input photo, remember, not a 3D scene,&nbsp; just a 2D photo, and now hold on to your papers&nbsp;&nbsp; Fellow Scholars for changing the time of day,&nbsp; my goodness, that looks absolutely incredible!&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Or just throw the lights out and make a cool&nbsp; nighttime scene with a new light source. So good! But how is that even possible? Well, step number&nbsp; one. To relight the scene first, we have to&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'de-light. Remove the lighting. No worries, that&nbsp; can be done with a previous paper. Easy-peasy. Now&nbsp;&nbsp; what? Of course, load it into Blender, and…wait&nbsp; a second. This is still just a 2D image, not a&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D scene. So now, step number two, let’s 3D-ify&nbsp; it. Once again, using the power of The Papers™,&nbsp;&nbsp; yes! We finally get a 3D scene. Hooray! And&nbsp; a newer problem. I mean, look, this is 3D,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'alright, but it does not look detailed at all.&nbsp; It even has holes in it! Let’s give it a try,&nbsp;&nbsp; render it with a new environment, and…uh…hello?&nbsp; The inaccurate 3D information is clear as day,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so we are kinda stuck. What do we do now? Dear Fellow Scholars, this&nbsp; is Two Minute Papers with&nbsp;&nbsp; Dr. Károly Zsolnai-Fehér. Dr. Carroll John Alpha.'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Well, let’s look at the good part. It’s now&nbsp; a 3D scene, so it’s a little virtual world,&nbsp;&nbsp; so new light sources can be added. Okay,&nbsp; so now, step number 3 let us beautify this&nbsp;&nbsp; scene…somehow. This is where the new paper&nbsp; comes in. The goal would be that this rough&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image would be re-rendered into a beautiful&nbsp; photo. Let’s call it a neural renderer where&nbsp;&nbsp; the input is a rough rendering, and the&nbsp; output is a real image it corresponds to. Of course, to be able to train&nbsp; a neural network like that,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we would need thousands of these pairs to train&nbsp; it on. Okay, if we look at the right part,&nbsp;&nbsp; this is trivial. The internet is&nbsp; full of photos, but what about&nbsp;&nbsp; rough 3D renderings that correspond to these&nbsp; photos? Well, of course, that’s the hard part.'

[02:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Earlier we said that we can produce 3D&nbsp; scenes from photos, but there is one problem. This is still not a perfect match. Why? Let’s&nbsp; see…because the lighting is different. We know the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scene from the photo, but we don’t yet know the&nbsp; kind of lighting that was used to produce it. For&nbsp;&nbsp; instance, the lights here aren’t really lights.&nbsp; So here’s the idea: let’s throw a few lights in&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there, render the scene, and see how different&nbsp; the result is from the target photo. Hmm…well,&nbsp;&nbsp; at this point, it is not close at all. Now, we&nbsp; wiggle them around a bit, and see if it is closer.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Repeat this process for thousands and thousands&nbsp; of photos, until the 3D scene with the lights&nbsp;&nbsp; really explains the photo. And now you have&nbsp; a proper neural network for neural rendering.'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And this is the key contribution here. Putting&nbsp; all of these together, you can now finally take&nbsp;&nbsp; a photo, and change it from night to daytime, or&nbsp; the other way around, remove lights, add lights.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Goodness, look! They even cast shadows! Spotlights&nbsp; and area lights also work, but it gets better,&nbsp;&nbsp; even animated projectors can be used so you can&nbsp; put yourself in the craziest ways onto any photo&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now. And this is why it’s a bit like the Mona Lisa&nbsp; at the laser-lit party. What a time to be alive! So, does this take hours to run per photo?&nbsp; Well, here is the best part: not at all,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all this runs in within three seconds.&nbsp; Two seconds for pre-processing,&nbsp;&nbsp; and relighting - less than a second. Crazy! Wow. And unfortunately, it breaks my heart that it&nbsp; flew under the radar - I hear almost nobody&nbsp;&nbsp;'

